**Not Selling Your Product is Selfish**

Nobody likes salesmen.

No one lies awake at night, sleeplessly excited for a salesman to come in the morning.

We think of salesmen as overbearing, greedy, and self-focused. Our chests tighten thinking about needing to shrug off yet another person trying to get us to buy over-priced things we don’t need.

Thus, when it’s our turn to sell, we carry this mindset with us and feel guilty.

*“These people don’t want to be bothered by my product.”*

*“They’ll think I’m just trying to make a sale.”*

We hate rejection, we hate ostracization: we hate selling.

However, what if it’s actually our *hatred* for selling that is selfish?

As a business owner, your goal is to provide solutions to people’s needs. You’re in business to help people, not hinder them or waste their time.

**Why the Salesmen are Hated...**

The Salesman Stereotype exists, not because they’re trying to sell a product, but because they sell it dishonestly. Whether it’s hidden fees, undisclosed problems, mismatched solutions, or just plain-old exaggeration, most people don’t trust salesmen.

If the goal in selling is solely to gain a buck, then yes, selling is selfish.

But if you believe you have a working product that will benefit buyers and is fairly priced, then it’s selfish *not* to offer it to the world.

Real salesmanship is not about tricking people into buying your products. True salesmen work with a potential client to see if their product fits with the customer’s needs. Your job as a businessperson is to serve your clientele by providing helpful products and services.

If what you’re offering isn’t worth selling, you should find what people truly need and sell that instead.

We all try to “sell” what we’re passionate about, whether a book, movie, sports team, vacation spot, or product we found helpful. For most of us, this is nothing more than playful bantering, a way to build camaraderie by “selling” one sports team over another. Nobody cynically asks what our hidden motive is.

Unfortunately, many people have experienced a salesperson whose goal was personal gain. When the salesperson receives personal benefit from a sale, people’s inner cynic jumps up and questions the motives. 

This is why we must be unwaveringly honest with our customers, explaining both the good and the bad. Our job is to work with the customer in deciding if we can actually help them. We must even be willing to lose a sale if our service is not best for the customer.

**Be willing to lose the sale...**

Losing a sale can feel awful. However, if your service is a poor fit for your prospect, the lost sale is actually a win\! Genuine fulfillment in our work and ultimate success come only as we serve others with integrity.

Our hatred of selling comes down to a deep misconception of what sales truly is. We dread being identified with people who have been dishonest or irresponsible. However, you’re job is to rise above that, to be a leader in salesmanship, and to raise others to a higher standard.  

As long as you avoid offering your valuable services to others because you fear rejection, you will rob the world of the gifts you possess and the good you could bring to people’s lives.
